1 Article – Family Law
2 5–527.1.
3 (a) IN THIS SECTION, “UNMET NEEDS” MEANS NEEDS BEYOND THOSE THAT
4 THE DEPARTMENT IS REQUIRED OR AGREES TO PAY, INCLUDING:
5 (1) ADDITIONAL SERVICES, RESOURCES, OR EQUIPMENT RELATED TO
6 A CHILD’S DISABILITY;
7 (2) HOUSING EXPENSES IF A CHILD IS PREPARING TO LEAVE THE
8 CUSTODY OF THE DEPARTMENT FOR REASONS RELATED TO THE CHILD’S AGE;
9 (3) TECHNOLOGY, SPECIAL CLOTHING, INSTRUMENTS, BOOKS, OR
10 OTHER ITEMS RELATING TO A CHILD’S HOBBIES AND INTERESTS;
11 (4) TRANSPORTATION EXPENSES NOT OTHERWISE PAID BY THE
12 DEPARTMENT; AND
13 (5) TUITION, TUTORING, OR TRAINING, INCLUDING APPLICATION
14 FEES, BOOKS, EQUIPMENT, AND TESTING.
15 (B) This section applies to children committed to the custody of the Department.
16 [(b) When applying for benefits under this section for a child in the Department’s
17 custody, the Department shall, in cooperation with the child’s attorney, identify a
18 representative payee or fiduciary in accordance with the requirements of 20 C.F.R. §§
19 404.2021 and 416.621.]
20 (C) IF A CHILD WAS RECEIVING U.S. DEPARTMENT OF VETERANS AFFAIRS
21 BENEFITS, SUPPLEMENTAL SECURITY INCOME, OR SOCIAL SECURITY BENEFITS
22 BEFORE ENTERING THE DEPARTMENT’S CUSTODY, OR IF THE DEPARTMENT
23 APPLIES FOR BENEFITS ON BEHALF OF THE CHILD, THE DEPARTMENT SHALL:
24 (1) ATTEMPT TO IDENTIFY, IN CONSULTATION WITH THE CHILD AND
25 THE CHILD’S GUARDIAN AD LITEM OR ATTORNEY, AN APPROPRIATE
26 REPRESENTATIVE PAYEE IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE REQUIREMENTS OF 20 C.F.R.
27 §§ 404.2021 AND 416.621;
28 (2) APPLY TO BECOME THE REPRESENTATIVE PAYEE ONLY IF NO
29 OTHER SUITABLE CANDIDATE IS AVAILABLE; AND
30 (3) DOCUMENT ALL EFFORTS TO LOCATE A SUITABLE CANDIDATE.

