19 (a) This section applies to children committed to the custody of the Department.
20 (b) When applying for benefits under this section for a child in the Department’s
21 custody, the Department shall, in cooperation with the child’s attorney, identify a
22 representative payee or fiduciary in accordance with the requirements of 20 C.F.R. §§
23 404.2021 and 416.621.
24 (c) Consistent with federal law, when the Department serves as the
25 representative payee or in any other fiduciary capacity for a child receiving [Veterans
26 Administration] U.S. DEPARTMENT OF VETERANS AFFAIRS benefits, Supplemental
27 Security Income, or Social Security benefits, the Department shall:
28 (1) use or conserve the benefits in the child’s best interest, including using
29 the benefits for services for special needs not otherwise provided by the Department or
30 conserving the benefits for the child’s reasonably foreseeable future needs;
31 (2) ensure that when the child attains the age of 14 years and until the
32 Department no longer serves as the representative payee or fiduciary, a minimum
33 percentage of the child’s benefits are not used to reimburse the State for the costs of care
34 for the child and are used or conserved in accordance with items (3) and (4) of this
35 subsection, as follows:

HOUSE BILL 768 7
1 (i) from age 14 through age 15, at least 40%;
2 (ii) from age 16 through age 17, at least 80%; and
3 (iii) from age 18 through age 20, 100%;
4 (3) for the child’s benefits or resources that are below or not subject to any
5 federal asset or resource limit, exercise discretion in accordance with federal law and in the
6 best interest of the child to conserve the funds or use the funds for services for special needs
7 not otherwise provided by the Department, including choosing one or more of the options
8 listed under item (4) of this subsection;
9 (4) appropriately monitor any federal asset or resource limits for the
10 benefits and ensure that the child’s best interest is served by using or conserving the
11 benefits in a way that avoids violating any federal asset or resource limits that would affect
12 the child’s eligibility to receive the benefits, including:
13 (i) applying to the Social Security Administration to establish a
14 Plan for Achieving Self–Support (PASS) account for the child under the Social Security Act
15 and determining whether it is in the best interest of the child to conserve all or part of the
16 benefits in the PASS account;
17 (ii) establishing a 529A plan for the child and conserving the child’s
18 benefits in that account in a manner that appropriately avoids any federal asset or resource
19 limits;
20 (iii) establishing an individual development account for the child and
21 conserving the child’s benefits in that account in a manner that appropriately avoids any
22 federal asset or resource limits;
23 (iv) establishing a special needs trust for the child and conserving the
24 child’s benefits in the trust in a manner that is consistent with federal requirements for
25 special needs trusts and that appropriately avoids any federal asset or resource limits;
26 (v) if the Department determines that using the benefits for services
27 for current special needs not already provided by the Department is in the best interests of
28 the child, using the benefits for those services;
29 (vi) if federal law requires certain back payments of benefits to be
30 placed in a dedicated account, complying with the requirements for dedicated accounts
31 under 20 C.F.R. § 416.640(e); and
32 (vii) applying any other exclusions from federal asset or resource
33 limits available under federal law and using or conserving the child’s benefits in a manner
34 that appropriately avoids any federal asset or resource limits;

